## 5. üìù Key Points

### 5.1. Responsive Testing Checklist
- [ ] Test at actual device sizes, not just breakpoints
- [ ] Test between breakpoints (e.g., 400px, 850px)
- [ ] Test in portrait and landscape orientations
- [ ] Test with real content (long names, missing images)
- [ ] Test touch interactions on actual devices
- [ ] Test with slow network (3G throttling)
- [ ] Test with different font size settings
- [ ] Check for horizontal scroll on all sizes
- [ ] Verify tap targets are minimum 44√ó44px
- [ ] Test forms with on-screen keyboard

### 5.2. Must Have
- Mobile-first approach with min-width media queries
- Flexible layouts using CSS Grid and Flexbox
- Responsive images with srcset and picture element
- Touch-friendly tap targets (minimum 44√ó44px)
- Proper viewport meta tag
- Content parity across devices

### 5.3. Do
- Start with mobile (320px) and enhance progressively
- Use relative units (rem, em, %) for flexibility
- Test on real devices, not just desktop browser
- Optimize images for different screen sizes
- Maintain semantic HTML order for accessibility
- Use clamp() for fluid typography
- Respect safe-area-inset on notched devices

### 5.4. Don't
- Don't start with desktop and scale down
- Don't hide important features on mobile
- Don't use fixed pixel widths for containers
- Don't create separate mobile/desktop sites
- Don't prevent user zoom (accessibility)
- Don't rely on hover-only interactions
- Don't make tap targets smaller than 44√ó44px

---

**Remember**: Responsive design is about creating one website that works everywhere, not multiple websites for different devices. Focus on flexible, content-driven layouts that adapt gracefully to any screen size.
